<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1436,152,1608]" pageId="5" pageNumber="20">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,330,654,680]" pageId="5" pageNumber="20">Discussion</emphasis>
:— 
<taxonomicName authority="J. M. Porter" authorityName="J. M. Porter" box="[367,1101,654,680]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Polemoniaceae" genus="Aliciella" kingdom="Plantae" order="Ericales" pageId="5" pageNumber="20" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="subSection" section="Aliciella" subSection="Subnudae">
<emphasis box="[367,466,655,680]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="20">Aliciella</emphasis>
Brand sect. 
<emphasis box="[630,729,655,680]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="20">Aliciella</emphasis>
subsect. 
<emphasis box="[849,964,655,680]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="20">Subnudae</emphasis>
J.M.Porter
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Porter, J. M." box="[1122,1320,654,680]" pageId="5" pageNumber="20" pagination="23 - 46" refId="ref9524" refString="Porter, J. M. (1998) Aliciella, a recircumscribed genus of Polemoniaceae. Aliso 17: 23 - 46." type="journal article" year="1998">Porter 1998: 31</bibRefCitation>
; see also 
<bibRefCitation author="Porter, J. M. &amp; Johnson, L. A." box="[151,442,693,719]" pageId="5" pageNumber="20" pagination="55 - 91" refId="ref9636" refString="Porter, J. M. &amp; Johnson, L. A. (2000) A phylogenetic classification of Polemoniaceae. Aliso 19: 55 - 91." type="journal article" year="2000">Porter and Johnson 2000</bibRefCitation>
) is largely of the 
<collectingRegion box="[646,755,693,719]" country="United States of America" name="Colorado" pageId="5" pageNumber="20">Colorado</collectingRegion>
Plateau. It boasts some of the more colorful and attractive members of the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Linnaeus" authorityYear="1753" box="[343,412,732,757]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Polemoniaceae" genus="Phlox" kingdom="Plantae" order="Ericales" pageId="5" pageNumber="20" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[343,412,732,757]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="20">Phlox</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
family in the Four Corners region, including 
<taxonomicName authority="(Greene ex Brand 1907: 119) J. M. Porter (1998: 33)" authorityName="J. M. Porter" authorityPageNumber="33" authorityYear="1998" baseAuthorityName="Greene ex Brand" baseAuthorityPageNumber="119" baseAuthorityYear="1907" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Polemoniaceae" genus="Aliciella" kingdom="Plantae" order="Ericales" pageId="5" pageNumber="20" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="formosa">
<emphasis box="[953,971,732,757]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="20">A</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[986,1082,732,757]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="20">formosa</emphasis>
(Greene ex 
<bibRefCitation author="Brand, A." box="[1228,1427,732,758]" pageId="5" pageNumber="20" pagination="250" refId="ref8765" refString="Brand, A. (1907) Polemoniaceae. Pp. 1 - 203. In: Das Pflanzenreich vol. 4: 250, ed A. Engler. Leipzig: W. Engelmann." type="journal article" year="1907">Brand 1907: 119</bibRefCitation>
) J.M. 
<bibRefCitation author="Porter, J. M." box="[198,421,770,796]" pageId="5" pageNumber="20" pagination="23 - 46" refId="ref9524" refString="Porter, J. M. (1998) Aliciella, a recircumscribed genus of Polemoniaceae. Aliso 17: 23 - 46." type="journal article" year="1998">Porter (1998: 33)</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="(Gray 1870: 276) J. M. Porter (1998: 33)" authorityName="J. M. Porter" authorityPageNumber="33" authorityYear="1998" baseAuthorityName="Gray" baseAuthorityPageNumber="276" baseAuthorityYear="1870" box="[436,1077,770,796]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Polemoniaceae" genus="Aliciella" kingdom="Plantae" order="Ericales" pageId="5" pageNumber="20" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="subnuda">
<emphasis box="[436,454,770,795]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="20">A</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[470,573,770,795]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="20">subnuda</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Gray, A." box="[591,788,770,796]" pageId="5" pageNumber="20" pagination="247 - 282" refId="ref9235" refString="Gray, A. (1870) Revision of North American Polemoniaceae. Proceedings of the American Academy of Arts and Sciences 8: 247 - 282." type="journal article" year="1870">Gray 1870: 276</bibRefCitation>
) J.M. 
<bibRefCitation author="Porter, J. M." box="[854,1077,770,796]" pageId="5" pageNumber="20" pagination="23 - 46" refId="ref9524" refString="Porter, J. M. (1998) Aliciella, a recircumscribed genus of Polemoniaceae. Aliso 17: 23 - 46." type="journal article" year="1998">Porter (1998: 33)</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="J. M. Porter" authorityYear="1998" baseAuthorityName="A. Gray" box="[1143,1284,770,796]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Polemoniaceae" genus="Aliciella" kingdom="Plantae" order="Ericales" pageId="5" pageNumber="20" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="haydenii">
<emphasis box="[1143,1161,770,795]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="20">A</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[1179,1284,770,795]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="20">haydenii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The showy magenta flowers of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="J. M. Porter" authorityYear="1998" baseAuthorityName="Greene ex Brand" baseAuthorityYear="1907" box="[383,511,809,835]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Polemoniaceae" genus="Aliciella" kingdom="Plantae" order="Ericales" pageId="5" pageNumber="20" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="formosa">
<emphasis box="[383,401,809,834]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="20">A</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[415,511,809,834]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="20">formosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="J. M. Porter" authorityYear="1998" baseAuthorityName="A. Gray" box="[567,700,809,835]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Polemoniaceae" genus="Aliciella" kingdom="Plantae" order="Ericales" pageId="5" pageNumber="20" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="haydenii">
<emphasis box="[567,585,809,834]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="20">A</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[599,700,809,834]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="20">haydenii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are hawkmoth pollinated, with over 90% of insect visits due to hawkmoths (Porter 1993; 
<bibRefCitation author="Porter, J. M. &amp; Floyd-Hanna, L." box="[455,808,848,874]" pageId="5" pageNumber="20" pagination="236 - 248" refId="ref9548" refString="Porter, J. M. &amp; Floyd-Hanna, L. (1993) A phylogenetic approach to natural historical and demographic explanations of rarity of Gilia formosa. Pp. 236 - 248. In: R. Sivinski and K. Lightfoot eds., Proceedings of the Southwestern rare and endangered plant conference. Miscellaneous publication No. 2. New Mexico Forestry and Resources Conservation Division, Energy, Minerals and Natural Resources Department, Santa Fe, New Mexico. 390 pp." type="book chapter" year="1993">Porter and Floyd-Hanna 1993</bibRefCitation>
). There are two subspecies of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="J. M. Porter" authorityYear="1998" baseAuthorityName="A. Gray" box="[1160,1293,848,874]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Polemoniaceae" genus="Aliciella" kingdom="Plantae" order="Ericales" pageId="5" pageNumber="20" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="haydenii">
<emphasis box="[1160,1178,848,873]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="20">A</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[1192,1293,848,873]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="20">haydenii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
recognized, differing in corolla size, density of glands on the external corolla, and in part corolla color upon drying. Regardless of these differences, populations and the two races of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="J. M. Porter" authorityYear="1998" baseAuthorityName="A. Gray" box="[937,1073,925,951]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Polemoniaceae" genus="Aliciella" kingdom="Plantae" order="Ericales" pageId="5" pageNumber="20" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="haydenii">
<emphasis box="[937,955,925,950]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="20">A</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[971,1073,925,950]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="20">haydenii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
share a common reproductive and pollination system (Porter 1993) and show some intergradation. This is consistent with the hypothesis that they represent a single species.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1436,152,1608]" pageId="5" pageNumber="20">
The series of isolated and disjunct populations near Beautiful Mountain, 
<collectingRegion box="[1101,1195,1041,1067]" country="United States of America" name="Arizona" pageId="5" pageNumber="20">Arizona</collectingRegion>
are very similar to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="J. M. Porter" authorityYear="1998" baseAuthorityName="A. Gray" box="[151,366,1080,1105]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Polemoniaceae" genus="Aliciella" kingdom="Plantae" order="Ericales" pageId="5" pageNumber="20" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="haydenii">
<emphasis box="[151,366,1080,1105]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="20">Aliciella haydenii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but differ in their narrower corolla tube and lobes and pale floral color, having blue to nearly white corollas (
<figureCitation box="[412,539,1118,1144]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,255,1074,1098]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,458,1050]" captionTargetId="figure-447@4.[151,1436,458,1050]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. A. Habit and architecture of Aliciella cliffordii, scale= 3.0 cm, J.M.Porter, K.D.Heil, &amp; A.Clifford 13528 (Photo J.M.Porter). B. Cymose inflorescence and flowers, scale= 5.0 mm, J.M.Porter, K.D.Heil, &amp; A.Clifford 13528 (Photo J.M.Porter). C. Bombilius sp. visiting flowers of Aliciella cliffordii, scale= 5.0 mm, J.M.Porter, K.D.Heil, &amp; A.Clifford 13528 (Photo J.M.Porter)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4906385" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4906385/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="20">Fig. 2A, B</figureCitation>
). The populations in the Beautiful Mountain area are pollinated primarily by beeflies (
<emphasis box="[272,511,1157,1182]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="20">Bombilius lancifer</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Osten Sacken, C. R." box="[521,860,1157,1183]" pageId="5" pageNumber="20" pagination="189 - 354" refId="ref9409" refString="Osten Sacken, C. R. (1877) Western Diptera: Descriptions of new genera and species of Diptera from the region west of the Mississippi and especially from California. U. S. Geological and Geographical Survey of the Territories Bulletin 8: 189 - 354" type="journal article" year="1877">Osten Sacken [1877: 251]</bibRefCitation>
; 
<figureCitation box="[876,976,1157,1183]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,255,1074,1098]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,458,1050]" captionTargetId="figure-447@4.[151,1436,458,1050]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. A. Habit and architecture of Aliciella cliffordii, scale= 3.0 cm, J.M.Porter, K.D.Heil, &amp; A.Clifford 13528 (Photo J.M.Porter). B. Cymose inflorescence and flowers, scale= 5.0 mm, J.M.Porter, K.D.Heil, &amp; A.Clifford 13528 (Photo J.M.Porter). C. Bombilius sp. visiting flowers of Aliciella cliffordii, scale= 5.0 mm, J.M.Porter, K.D.Heil, &amp; A.Clifford 13528 (Photo J.M.Porter)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4906385" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4906385/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="20">Fig. 2C</figureCitation>
), and visited, to a lesser degree, by anthophorid bees, representing an ethological distinction from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="J. M. Porter" authorityYear="1998" baseAuthorityName="A. Gray" box="[920,1059,1196,1222]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Polemoniaceae" genus="Aliciella" kingdom="Plantae" order="Ericales" pageId="5" pageNumber="20" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="haydenii">
<emphasis box="[920,938,1196,1221]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="20">A</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[955,1059,1196,1221]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="20">haydenii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Field studies over a four-year period, summing to nearly 200 hours of observation time, have verified that these populations are not visited by hawkmoths, rather 
<emphasis box="[424,442,1273,1298]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="20">B</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[459,553,1273,1298]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="20">lancifer</emphasis>
(73% of visits) and several species of anthophorid bees (18% of visits). Nonpollinating visitors (e.g., syrphid flies) account for the remaining visits. I hypothesize that the populations near Beautiful Mountain correspond to a different reproductive and pollination system from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="J. M. Porter" authorityYear="1998" baseAuthorityName="A. Gray" box="[1244,1378,1350,1376]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Polemoniaceae" genus="Aliciella" kingdom="Plantae" order="Ericales" pageId="5" pageNumber="20" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="haydenii">
<emphasis box="[1244,1262,1351,1376]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="20">A</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[1277,1378,1351,1376]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="20">haydenii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and therefore comprise a genetically independent species. In accordance, I treat it at the rank of species. While 
<taxonomicName authorityName="J. M. Porter" authorityYear="2011" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Polemoniaceae" genus="Aliciella" kingdom="Plantae" order="Ericales" pageId="5" pageNumber="20" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="cliffordii">
<emphasis box="[1411,1429,1389,1414]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="20">A</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[151,256,1428,1453]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="20">cliffordii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
seems technically weak if considering the morphological features alone, the different pollination system and geographic disjunction is consistent with a hypothesis of peripatric speciation, involving a change in pollination mechanisms. This provides an explicit hypothesis that can be experimentally tested. It is also important to note that, in the field, it is readily distinguishable from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="J. M. Porter" authorityYear="1998" baseAuthorityName="A. Gray" box="[948,1082,1544,1570]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Polemoniaceae" genus="Aliciella" kingdom="Plantae" order="Ericales" pageId="5" pageNumber="20" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="haydenii">
<emphasis box="[948,966,1544,1569]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="20">A</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[981,1082,1544,1569]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="20">haydenii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[1098,1225,1544,1570]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="6.[151,257,862,886]" captionTargetBox="[154,1436,153,834]" captionTargetId="figure-184@6.[154,1440,153,835]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 3. A. Habit and architecture of Aliciella haydenii, scale= 3.0 cm, J.M.Porter &amp; K.D.Heil 12455, (Photo J.M.Porter). B. Cymose inflorescence and flowers, scale= 3.0 mm, J.M.Porter &amp; K.D.Heil 12455, (Photo J.M.Porter)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4906387" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4906387/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="20">Fig. 3A, B</figureCitation>
). The two species can be distinguished using the following key:
</paragraph>
